courses.name: The Real World of Politics: An Introduction

primaryOrg.name: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

cmCourseInfo.description: This course introduces students to compelling issues of contemporary politics through the lens of classic and important texts in political science. The course covers the politics of climate change, Indigenous rights, elections and electoral systems, terrorism, social movements and political activism, voting, democracy, and power.
cmCourseInfo.title: The Real World of Politics: An Introduction

notes.name: Course Note
notes.content:
Timetable Instructions

Delivery Method:

  • Lecture:  Online Asynchronous
  • Tutorials:   Online Synchronous

Note:  Tutorial enrolment is mandatory.  

All students are required to enrol in a tutorial at the time of course enrolment. 

Enrol in a section that works with your schedule.

Delivery Instructions

  • Lectures will be delivered online; learning is self-paced and not reliant on a meeting schedule.
  • Recordings of lecture will also be available for students to view asynchronously.
  • All tutorials will be available as online synchronous.
  • It is recommended that students have a computer with a microphone and camera in order to participate in online activities.
  • Tutorial enrolment is mandatory.
  • Please enrol in a tutorial section that works with your schedule.

cmCourseInfo.description: Examines major facets of Canadian government and politics within a broad comparative context asking what is different or unique about Canada and what resembles political systems elsewhere in the world, primarily western industrialized countries. Comparative analysis is used to foster a deeper understanding of Canada and its politics. [24L, 11T]
cmCourseInfo.title: Canada in Comparative Perspective

cmCourseInfo.description: Examines current ideas about what constitutes 'democracy' and how real-world political systems measure up to democratic ideals. Through examination of formal government institutions and informal political practices, assessments will be made of the strengths and weaknesses in modern democracies. Case studies may be drawn from Canada or from other countries which claim to be democratic. [24L, 11T]
cmCourseInfo.title: Democracy in Theory and Practice

cmCourseInfo.description: Examines the politics of globalization in its various forms (economics, cultures, environmental and military) as well as the consequences of, management of and resistance to, globalization. Address topics such as whether globalization challenges the capacity of national societies and their governments to deal with global issues such as the environment, redistribution of wealth, security and human rights, both within countries and across borders.
cmCourseInfo.title: Politics in a Global World

courses.name: Political Theory: Visions of the Just/Good Society

primaryOrg.name: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

cmCourseInfo.description: A selective presentation of critical encounters between philosophy and politics, dedicated to the quest for articulation and founding of the just/good society. Among the theorists examined are Plato, Aristotle, Machiavelli, Hobbes and Locke.
cmCourseInfo.title: Political Theory: Visions of the Just/Good Society

courses.name: Immigration, Multiculturalism, and Citizenship in Canada

primaryOrg.name: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

cmCourseInfo.description: This course deals with three inter-related themes – immigration, multiculturalism, and citizenship – by focusing on a single unifying question: What does it mean to “belong” to the Canadian political community? Who belongs, on what terms, and to what ends? A range of materials – normative, empirical, historical, and contemporary – will be used.
cmCourseInfo.title: Immigration, Multiculturalism, and Citizenship in Canada
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: 4.0 credits, or 1.0 credit in POL/ JPA/ JPF/ JPI/ JPR/ JPS/ JRA courses

courses.name: Colonial Legacies and Post-Independence African Politics

primaryOrg.name: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

cmCourseInfo.description: This course highlights the critical roles of pre-colonial and colonial histories in shaping contemporary political and economic developments in Africa. It covers the emergence of colonial states, the central legacies of colonial rule, and the impact of colonialism in shaping process of state and nation building from independence to the present.

courses.name: Politics and Society in 20th Century China

primaryOrg.name: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

cmCourseInfo.description: This course examines China’s efforts to reconstitute its political institutions following the collapse of the imperial system in 1911. Particular attention is paid to the clash between competing conceptions of political development and the rival political movements and forces that espoused them. The search for an effective and stable political order is a major focus of the course.
cmCourseInfo.title: Politics and Society in 20th Century China

courses.name: The Politics of U.S. Foreign Policy

primaryOrg.name: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

cmCourseInfo.description: This course explores the making of foreign policy in the U.S. through a detailed examination of the institutions of the U.S. government involved, as well as the forces acting upon them to shape policy. After exploring theoretical approaches to the subject, it examines the evolution of the constitutional context within which U.S. foreign policy has been articulated, the bureaucracies involved in shaping policy, the impact of elections, groups and the mass media.
cmCourseInfo.title: The Politics of U.S. Foreign Policy
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: POL208H1/POL208Y1/POL209H5/POLB80H3

cmCourseInfo.description: The course provides an in-depth introduction to theories of the origins of democracy and dictatorship. In the first part of the course, we examine and compare theories rooted in economic development, voluntarism, institutional design, and historical institutionalism. The latter half of the course applies these different approaches to debates over the origins of Nazi rule in Germany in the 1930s, military dictatorship in Chile in the 1970s, and non-democratic rule in contemporary Russia.
cmCourseInfo.title: Democracy and Dictatorship
